[[File:Shirahige bashi.jpg|thumb|200px|From Arakawa Ward, Tokyo (January 2008)]] {{Ja_Pref_Route_Sign|pref=Tokyo|number=306|align=left}} [[File:Shirahigebashi-sundown-side-april28-2015.jpg|thumb|200px|From Sumida Ward, Tokyo (April 2015)]] [[File:Shirahigebashi-fromskytree-2016 4 9.jpg|thumb|200px|From Tokyo Skytree (April 2016)]]
'''Shirahige Bridge''' (白鬚橋, ''Shirahige-bashi'') is a bridge spanning the {{ill|Sumida River|ja|隅田川|12=draft|12=draft}}, carrying the {{ill|Tokyo Metropolitan Route 306|ja|東京都道306号王子千住夢の島線|12=draft|12=draft}} (commonly known as Meiji-dōri). The western bank separates {{ill|Minami-Senju|ja|南千住|12=draft|12=draft}}, Arakawa Ward, from {{ill|Hashiba|ja|橋場|12=draft|12=draft}}, Taitō Ward, while the eastern bank divides {{ill|Tsuijidō|ja|堤通|12=draft|12=draft}} 1 and 2-chōme in Sumida Ward. The bridge takes its name from the nearby {{ill|Shirahige Shrine|ja|白鬚神社|12=draft|12=draft}}. Note that the correct kanji for the name is "鬚" (chin whiskers), often mistakenly written as "髭" (moustache).
== History == The bridge was first constructed in May 1914 (Taishō 3). Local residents raised funds to establish the Shirahige Bridge Corporation, beginning construction in April 1913 (Taishō 2). The wooden bridge was completed within a year, measuring approximately 130 ken (about 230 meters) in length. A toll of one sen per person was charged<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=The History of the Sumida River as Seen from Its Bridges|author=飯田雅男|publisher=Bungeisha|date=2002-06|page=212|isbn=4-8355-3894-3}}</ref>, but competition from ferry services made it challenging to maintain operations. Despite doubling the toll to two sen, the company struggled to maintain the bridge, eventually selling it to Tokyo Prefecture in 1925 (Taishō 14).
Although it suffered no damage during the {{ill|1923 Great Kantō Earthquake|ja|関東大震災|12=draft|12=draft}}, the urban planning project for the city's first-class ring road (Route No. 16, now Meiji-dōri) necessitated replacing the wooden bridge with the current iron bridge.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Bridges of Sumida River|publisher=Sumida Ward Green Library|date=1993-03|series=Sumida Ward Library Series 8|page=61}}</ref>
The location was originally home to the "{{ill|Hashiba Ferry|ja|橋場の渡し|12=draft|12=draft}}" and "{{ill|Shirahige Ferry|ja|白鬚の渡し|12=draft|12=draft}}," with Hashiba Ferry serving as a primary crossing point on the Sumida River during the Edo period until the construction of {{ill|Senju Bridge|ja|千住大橋|12=draft|12=draft}} in Bunroku 3 (1594). The famous "Kototoi no Uta" poem from the {{ill|Tales of Ise|ja|伊勢物語|12=draft|12=draft}}, attributed to {{ill|Ariwara no Narihira|ja|在原業平|12=draft|12=draft}}, was composed at this crossing.
== Bridge Specifications == * '''Structure type''': Through-arch braced ribbed bridge * '''Length''': 167.6 meters<ref name=":0" /> * '''Width''': 24.1 meters<ref name=":0" /> * '''Steel weight''': 1,923 tons<ref name=":0" /> * '''Construction started''': Shōwa 3 (1928) July<ref name=":0" /> * '''Completed''': Shōwa 6 (1931) June<ref name=":0" /> * '''Contractor''': Tokyo Prefecture * '''Designer''': {{ill|Jun Masuda|ja|増田淳|12=draft|12=draft}} * '''Bridge girder manufacturer''': Kawasaki Dockyard * '''Similar design''': {{ill|Asahi Bridge (Asahikawa)|ja|旭橋 (旭川市)|12=draft|12=draft}}
== Public Transportation == * '''{{ill|Toei Bus|ja|都営バス|12=draft|12=draft}}''' ** {{ill|Route 22|ja|都営バス南千住営業所#里22系統|12=draft|12=draft}}: {{ill|Ni11ori Station|ja|日暮里駅|12=draft|12=draft}} - {{ill|Mikawashima Station|ja|三河島駅|12=draft|12=draft}} - {{ill|Arakawa Ward Office|ja|荒川区役所|12=draft|12=draft}} - Namidabashi - Hashiba 2-chōme - Higashi Mukōjima Hirokōji - {{ill|Kameido Station|ja|亀戸駅|12=draft|12=draft}}
== Cultural References == * Sōtome Katsumoto's ''Beautiful Bridge'' (美しい橋)<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Stories of Bridges|publisher=Sumida Ward Education Committee|date=1983-03|page=13}}</ref>
== Nearby Bridges == * {{ill|Sumida River|ja|隅田川|12=draft|12=draft}} : (Upstream) - {{ill|Senju Shiomi Bridge|ja|千住汐入大橋|12=draft|12=draft}} - {{ill|Suijin Bridge|ja|水神大橋|12=draft|12=draft}} * '''Shirahige Bridge''' - {{ill|Sakura Bridge (Tokyo)|ja|桜橋 (東京都)|12=draft|12=draft}} - {{ill|Kototoi Bridge|ja|言問橋|12=draft|12=draft}} - (Downstream) == See Also == * {{ill|Arakawa Under the Bridge|ja|荒川アンダー ザ ブリッジ|12=draft|12=draft}} (A manga that features this bridge in several scenes)
== References == {{Reflist}}
== External Links == * [http://library.jsce.or.jp/jscelib/committee/2003/bridge/A5-027.htm Detailed Data on Shirahige Bridge] (via the [http://www.jsce.or.jp/library/ Japan Society of Civil Engineers Digital Library])
