== History == The bridge was first constructed in May 1914 (Taishō 3). Local residents raised funds to establish the Shirahige Bridge Corporation, beginning construction in April 1913 (Taishō 2). The wooden bridge was completed within a year, measuring approximately 130 ken (about 230 meters) in length. A toll of one sen per person was charged<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=The History of the Sumida River as Seen from Its Bridges|author=飯田雅男|publisher=Bungeisha|date=2002-06|page=212|isbn=4-8355-3894-3}}</ref>, but competition from ferry services made it challenging to maintain operations. Despite doubling the toll to two sen, the company struggled to maintain the bridge, eventually selling it to Tokyo Prefecture in 1925 (Taishō 14).
Although it suffered no damage during the {{ill|1923 Great Kantō Earthquake|ja|関東大震災|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the urban planning project for the city's first-class ring road (Route No. 16, now Meiji-dōri) necessitated replacing the wooden bridge with the current iron bridge.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Bridges of Sumida River|publisher=Sumida Ward Green Library|date=1993-03|series=Sumida Ward Library Series 8|page=61}}</ref>
The location was originally home to the "{{ill|Hashiba Ferry|ja|橋場の渡し|qq=draft|qq=draft}}" and "{{ill|Shirahige Ferry|ja|白鬚の渡し|qq=draft|qq=draft}}," with Hashiba Ferry serving as a primary crossing point on the Sumida River during the Edo period until the construction of {{ill|Senju Bridge|ja|千住大橋|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Bunroku 3 (1594). The famous "Kototoi no Uta" poem from the {{ill|Tales of Ise|ja|伊勢物語|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, attributed to {{ill|Ariwara no Narihira|ja|在原業平|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, was composed at this crossing.
== Bridge Specifications == * '''Structure type''': Through-arch braced ribbed bridge * '''Length''': 167.6 meters<ref name=":0" /> * '''Width''': 24.1 meters<ref name=":0" /> * '''Steel weight''': 1,923 tons<ref name=":0" /> * '''Construction started''': Shōwa 3 (1928) July<ref name=":0" /> * '''Completed''': Shōwa 6 (1931) June<ref name=":0" /> * '''Contractor''': Tokyo Prefecture * '''Designer''': {{ill|Jun Masuda|ja|増田淳|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * '''Bridge girder manufacturer''': Kawasaki Dockyard * '''Similar design''': {{ill|Asahi Bridge (Asahikawa)|ja|旭橋 (旭川市)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
